  <!-- Section: FAQ -->
  <section id="faq" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

    <div class="space-y-6">
      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Why is there no income requirement?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Aruba designed the program to be accessible. They rely on accommodation and insurance requirements to ensure visitors can support themselves. The focus is on welcoming remote workers, not creating barriers.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Can I extend beyond 90 days?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Yes, extensions are possible. You'll need to apply with immigration before your 90 days expire. Requirements may include proof of continued employment and insurance.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">What's the best time to visit?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Aruba is sunny year-round with minimal rainfall. High season (December-April) has best weather but highest prices. Low season (May-November) is slightly cheaper and still beautiful—remember, Aruba's outside the hurricane belt.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">How's the internet?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Generally good with 50-100 Mbps available in most areas. Check specific properties before booking. Coworking spaces in Oranjestad offer reliable connectivity.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Do I need a car?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Helpful but not essential if you stay in tourist areas with beaches nearby. For exploring the whole island (highly recommended), a car or scooter makes sense. Public transit is limited.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">What about wind?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Aruba is windy—great for kiteboarding and windsurfing, less great if you hate wind. Trade winds are constant. The west coast (Palm Beach, Eagle Beach) is calmer than the east.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

